{"title_page": "Watkin Tudor Jones", "text_new": "{{Use South African English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| birth_name       = Watkin Tudor Jones\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|9|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| image            = File:Die Antwoord Ninja on the street.jpg\n| caption          = Watkin Tudor Jones (Ninja) in 2012\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias    siiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii    = {{hlist|Ninja|Max Normal|The Man Who Never Came Back|MC Totally Rad|Yang Weapon|Destructo|Waddy|WAD:e<ref name=\"Jones - Levi's Original Music Magazine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.levis.co.za/MusicMag/Category/Detail/Detail.aspx?ID=790|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324023824/http://www.levis.co.za/MusicMag/Category/Detail/Detail.aspx?ID=790|archivedate=2010-03-24|title=Anything But Normal (archived)|publisher=Levi's Original Music Magazine|date=9 September 2008|url-status=live|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>|Ninjie<ref>Donker Mag (album), Raging Zef Boner (track 5), line 1 and repeated throughout track (lyrics)</ref>}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Alternative hip hop]]|[[electronica]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|songwriter|record producer|actor|music video director}}\n| years_active     = 1995\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[Cherrytree Records|Cherrytree]]<ref name=\"BBsigned\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boingboing.net/2010/03/12/die-antwoord-signed.html |title=Die Antwoord to sign with Interscope, Neill Blomkamp to direct next video |publisher=Boing Boing |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|Rhythm|Zef}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Yolandi Visser]]|The Original Evergreen|[[MaxNormal.TV]]|[[The Constructus Corporation]]|Fucknrad|[[Die Antwoord]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Watkin Tudor Jones''' (born 26 September 1974),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxnormal.tv/interview2.php |title=Max Normal - Music, Movies, Merchandise |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2007-03-05 |accessdate=2015-09-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071208213204/http://www.maxnormal.tv/interview2.php |archivedate=8 December 2007 }}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Ninja''', is a [[South Africa]]n rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer, actor, and director. He is best known for being in the [[rap-rave]] group [[Die Antwoord]]. Jones also has had a number of acting roles, including a self-styled role as Ninja in the 2015 [[Neill Blomkamp]] film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-cast-die-antwoord-in-chappie-what-is-zef-was-all-the-obvious-product-pl|title=Why cast Die Antwoord in \"Chappie\"? What is Zef? Was all the obvious product placement good or bad {{!}} ScreenPrism|last=ScreenPrism|website=screenprism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJones was born in [[Johannesburg|Johannesburg, South Africa]] in 1974. \n\nAccording to [[Die Antwoord]] bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]], Jones has been on the South African hip hop scene since he was 13. He frequented nightclubs where he would develop his skills as a rapper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/23706/1/yo-landi-visser-dark-star|title=Yo-landi Visser\u2019s rise from hood rat to heroine|last=Dazed|date=2015-02-26|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1995\u20131996: The Original Evergreen ===\nJones was part of the South African rap band The Original Evergreen, which were signed to [[Sony Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/FeaturesInterviews/24-Facts-Die-Antwoord-20100204|title=24 Facts: Die Antwoord|last=Barker|first=Jean|date=2010-02-04|website=Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> He released one single with the group, 'Puff the Magik', which was banned from radio for its controversial lyrics about [[marajuana]] usage. He left in 1996 to release a solo album under Chameleon Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1147517-The-Original-Evergreen|title=The Original Evergreen|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2001\u20132002: ''Memoirs Of A Clone'' and Max Normal ===\nIn 2001, Jones released his debut solo album ''Memoirs Of A Clone.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Watkin-Tudor-Jones-Jnr-Memoirs-Of-A-Clone/release/1174704|title=Watkin Tudor Jones Jnr.* \u2013 Memoirs Of A Clone|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, he was the lead vocalist of Max Normal, a hip hop act, which released their debut album entitled ''Songs From The Mall'' in 2001, which he disbanded in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/620890-Max-Normal|title=Max Normal|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> Their last gig was played with [[Faithless]] on the group's 2002 South Africa tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/FeaturesInterviews/24-Facts-Die-Antwoord-20100204|title=24 Facts: Die Antwoord|last=Barker|first=Jean|date=2010-02-04|website=Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n=== 2002\u20132003: ''The Constructus Corporation''===\n{{main|The Constructus Corporation}}\nWhen Jones disbanded Max Normal in early 2002, he and musician Sibot invited [[Markus Wormstorm]] and [[Felix Laband]] to collaborate on The Constructus Corporation project, which resulted in the concept album and graphic novel ''[[The Ziggurat (Constructus Corporation album)|The Ziggurat]],'' released on 3 June 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africandope.co.za/albums/ziggurat.htm |title=Ziggurat \u2013 African Dope Records |publisher=Africandope.co.za |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> \n\nJones asked Anri du Toit, better known as his Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]] to lend vocals for the project. She was credited as Anica the Snuffling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netzpiloten.de/high-energy-shit-%e2%80%93-%c2%b4die-antwoord%c2%b4-klettern-aus-dem-netz/|title=High Energy Shit \u2013 Die Antwoord klettern aus dem Netz \u2013 Netzpiloten.de|date=2010-08-27|website=Netzpiloten Magazin|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThe Constructus Corporation disbanded in 2003.\n\n=== 2005: ''The Fantastic Kill'' ===\nIn 2005, Jones released his second solo album ''The Fantastic Kill.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Watkin-Tudor-Jones-The-Fantastic-Kill/release/1283679|title=Watkin Tudor Jones \u2013 The Fantastic Kill|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> It was released in France in 2007 as ''MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck Are Fucknrad'' under the name Fucknrad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Fucknrad-MC-Totally-Rad-And-DJ-Fuck-Are-Fucknrad/release/1332825|title=Fucknrad \u2013 MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck Are Fucknrad|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007\u20132008: MaxNormal.TV ===\n{{main|MaxNormal.TV}}\nIn 2007, Jones resurrected and revamped Max Normal as the 'corporate' hip-hop group \"MaxNormal.TV.\" \n\nThe new lineup consisted of Watkin Tudor Jones revising as Max Normal, and Anri du Toit as [[Yolandi Visser]]. The band also featured Neon Don playing various recurring characters and [[Justin De Nobrega]] making instrumentals.\n\nThe group released their debut and only album ''Good Morning South Africa'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/MaxNormalTV-Good-Morning-South-Africa/release/1636872|title=MaxNormal.TV \u2013 Good Morning South Africa|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> A DVD featuring 13 skits, music videos and short films was released in the same year, titled ''Goeie More Zuid Afrika.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/MaxNormalTV-Goeie-More-Zuid-Africa/release/7143103|title=MaxNormal.TV \u2013 Goeie More Zuid Africa|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008\u2013present: Die Antwoord ===\n{{main|Die Antwoord}}\nJones is currently a member of the South African rap-rave group [[Die Antwoord]]. The group was formed by Jones as Ninja, Anri du Toit as [[Yolandi Visser|\u00a5o-Landi Vi$$er]] and producer [[Die Antwoord|Justin De Nobrega]] as HITEK5000 (formerly referred to as DJ Hi-Tek and God). They have since added a second producer Lil2Hood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dieantwoord.com/about/|title=About|website=Die Antwoord|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Die Antwoord is part of the South African counterculture movement known as [[Zef]]. \n\nThe band released their debut album ''[[$O$]]'' in 2009. It was made freely available online and attracted international attention for their music video \"Enter the Ninja\". They briefly signed with [[Interscope Records]], and left after pressure from the label to be more generic. du Toit explained that Interscope \"kept pushing us to be more generic\" in order to make more money: \"If you try to make songs that other people like, your band will always be shit. You always gotta do what you like. If it connects, it's a miracle, but it happened with Die Antwoord.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/02/die-antwoords-totally-insane-words-wisdom/|title=Die Antwoord\u2019s Totally Insane Words of Wisdom|date=2012-02-07|website=Spin|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>. They formed their own [[Independent record label|independent label]], Zef Recordz and released their second album [[Tension (Die Antwoord album)|''Tension'']] through it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2011/11/07/dieantwoordleave.html|title=Die Antwoord leave Interscope, will release \"TEN$ION\" on their own new indie label|date=2011-11-07|website=Boing Boing|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThey have since released 2 other albums; [[Donker Mag|''Donker Mag'']] in 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/die_antwoord_return_with_donker_mag_album_share_new_video|title=Die Antwoord Reveal 'Donker Mag' LP, Share New Video|website=exclaim.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>, and [[Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid|''Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid'']] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19617/reviews/4150414|title=Album Review: Die Antwoord \u2013 Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> As well as this, Jones played a self-styled role as Ninja in the 2015 [[Neill Blomkamp]] film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-cast-die-antwoord-in-chappie-what-is-zef-was-all-the-obvious-product-pl|title=Why cast Die Antwoord in \"Chappie\"? What is Zef? Was all the obvious product placement good or bad {{!}} ScreenPrism|last=ScreenPrism|website=screenprism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n=== Zheani Sparkes and sexual assault allegations ===\nIn March 2019, [[Australian]] musician Zheani Sparkes released a [[Diss Track|diss track]] titled \"The Question\" detailing an alleged sexual assault on her by Jones in South Africa in 2013. Sparkes claimed that Jones drugged her, as well as human traffick[ed] her to Africa, and sent sexually explicit photos of her to cast members of [[Chappie (film)|''Chappie'']]. He also expressed having an active interest in her because of her resemblance to his now teenage daughter, Sixteen Jones, who in 2013, was only 8 years old.<ref>{{Citation|title=ZHEANI - THE QUESTION|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY6hCE2D-cc|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allmetaleverything.com/what-happened-with-zheani-and-die-antwoord/|title=What Happened with Zheani and Die Antwoord?!|date=2019-03-11|website=All Metal Everything|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/aussie-rapper-accuses-die-antwoords-ninja-of-trafficking-child-grooming-sexual-abuse-more-in-explosive-new-diss-track/|title=Aussie Rapper Accuses Die Antwoord Of \"Trafficking\", Sexual Abuse & More In Explosive New Diss Track|date=2019-03-21|website=Music Feeds|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nA conflict between Die Antwoord and Sparkes ensued on social media afterwards, where Jones accused Sparkes of catfishing him.<ref>{{Citation|title=DIE ANTWOORD - CATFISH #\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddfa\ud83d\udc31\ud83d\udc1f|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xW_JiG-3DNk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In September 2019, Sparkes filed a police report in [[Queensland|Queensland, Australia]] formalizing her accusations of sexual assault and [[revenge porn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/zheani-die-antwoord-ninja/|title=Zheani pressing sexual assault charges against Die Antwoord\u2019s Ninja|date=2019-09-16|website=Tone Deaf|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nItalian-American singer [[Dionna Dal Monte]] also accused Jones of sexual assault, which she claimed occurred at a Die Antwoord show in 2014. Jones has vehemently denied all these allegations.<ref name=\"SMH2\">{{Cite news|last=Bossi|first=Dominic|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/australian-woman-accuses-die-antwoord-singer-ninja-of-sexual-assault-20190904-p52nv7.html|title=Australian woman accuses Die Antwoord singer Ninja of sexual assault|date=15 September 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Fight against Andy Butler ===\nIn 2019, a video from 2012 surfaced, showing Jones and Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]] fighting [[Hercules and Love Affair]] founder Andy Butler while calling him insults that could be seen as [[Homophobia|homophobic]], such as \"[[Faggot (slang)|faggot]]\". Butler openly identifies as gay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefullest.com/2017/08/29/hercules-love-affairs-andy-butler-business-gay/|title=Hercules and Love Affair\u2019s Andy Butler on the Business of Being Gay|last=says|first=Karrie|date=2017-08-29|website=The Fullest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> After fighting him, Visser and Jones alert security staff, and, while crying, Visser claims she was [[Sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] in a bathroom by Butler. Later on in the video, Jones tells her that her performance was \"[[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/die-antwoord-removed-festivals-homophobic-attack-hercules-love-affair-andy-butler-2539949|title=Die Antwoord axed from festivals for 'homophobic attack' on Andy Butler|date=2019-08-20|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Yolandi makes fake sexual assault allegations. One night in Adelaide.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rL1lqrRj9C0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nJones responded on [[Facebook]], claiming that the person who filmed the video edited it to make it seem like he and Visser were in the wrong. He claims that Butler harassed them in the days leading up to the fight, and that it had nothing to do with him being gay. Jones also claimed that he told Visser to act as \"dramatic as possible\" about what Butler did to avoid getting detained by security after the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DieAntwoord/posts/10157192229201971|title=DIE ANTWOORD|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nDie Antwoord was subsequently dropped from the lineup of several upcoming festivals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Norris|first=Chelsey|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/can-die-antwoord-survive-their-latest-in-string-of-scandals-11764757|title=Die Antwoord Reschedules Dallas Show Amid Controversy. We're Not Surprised.|date=26 September 2019|work=Dallas Observer|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones has a daughter, Sixteen Jones, born in 2005 from a previous relationship with Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2oceansvibe.com/2012/02/02/meet-sixteen-the-daugther-of-ninja-and-yolani-vier/|title=Meet Sixteen, The Daugther [sic] Of Ninja And Yolani Vi$$er \u2013 2oceansvibe.com|website=www.2oceansvibe.com|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> He also has 3 adopted children. Tokkie and his sister Meisie were adopted in 2010, and Jemile was adopted in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dieantwoord.com/yoho-magazine/|title=YOHO! MAGAZINE|date=2019-12-03|website=Die Antwoord|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== The Original Evergreen ===\n\n* ''Puff The Magik'' (1995)\n\n=== Max Normal ===\n\n* ''Songs From the Mall'' (2001)\n\n=== The Constructus Corporation ===\n\n* ''[[The Ziggurat (Constructus Corporation album)|The Ziggurat]]'' (2003)\n\n=== MaxNormal.TV ===\n\n* ''Rap Made Easy'' (2007)\n* ''Good Morning South Africa'' (2008)\n\n=== Die Antwoord ===\n\n* ''[[$O$]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Ten$Ion|TEN$ION]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Donker Mag]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Mount Ninji and Da Nice Time Kid]]'' (2016)\n* ''The House of Zef'' (TBA 2020)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Memoirs Of A Clone'' (2001)\n* ''The Fantastic Kill'' (2005) (released in 2007 in France as ''MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck are Fucknrad'')\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Goeie More Zuid Africa DVD'' (2008)\n* ''Tokoloshe'' (2011)\n* ''Umshimi Wam'' (2011)\n* ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]'' (2015) \u2013 features \"Baby's On Fire\", \"Ugly Boy\", \"Cookie Thumper\" and \"Enter the Ninja\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3333301/die-antwoord-featured-latest-chappie-featurette/|title=Die Antwoord Featured In Latest \u2018Chappie\u2019 Featurette|last=JonathanBarkan|date=2015-02-20|website=Bloody Disgusting!|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{IMDb name|4375135}}\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Watkin+Tudor+Jones Watkin Tudor Jones Discography at discogs.com]\n\n{{Die Antwoord}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Watkin Tudor}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Afrikaans-language singers]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Cape Town culture]]\n[[Category:South African dance musicians]]\n[[Category:South African hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:South African rappers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Die Antwoord members]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Parktown Boys' High School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use South African English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| birth_name       = Watkin Tudor Jones\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|9|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| image            = File:Die Antwoord Ninja on the street.jpg\n| caption          = Watkin Tudor Jones (Ninja) in 2012\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = {{hlist|Ninja|Max Normal|The Man Who Never Came Back|MC Totally Rad|Yang Weapon|Destructo|Waddy|WAD:e<ref name=\"Jones - Levi's Original Music Magazine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.levis.co.za/MusicMag/Category/Detail/Detail.aspx?ID=790|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324023824/http://www.levis.co.za/MusicMag/Category/Detail/Detail.aspx?ID=790|archivedate=2010-03-24|title=Anything But Normal (archived)|publisher=Levi's Original Music Magazine|date=9 September 2008|url-status=live|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>|Ninjie<ref>Donker Mag (album), Raging Zef Boner (track 5), line 1 and repeated throughout track (lyrics)</ref>}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Alternative hip hop]]|[[electronica]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|songwriter|record producer|actor|music video director}}\n| years_active     = 1995\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|[[Cherrytree Records|Cherrytree]]<ref name=\"BBsigned\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boingboing.net/2010/03/12/die-antwoord-signed.html |title=Die Antwoord to sign with Interscope, Neill Blomkamp to direct next video |publisher=Boing Boing |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref>|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|Rhythm|Zef}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Yolandi Visser]]|The Original Evergreen|[[MaxNormal.TV]]|[[The Constructus Corporation]]|Fucknrad|[[Die Antwoord]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Watkin Tudor Jones''' (born 26 September 1974),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxnormal.tv/interview2.php |title=Max Normal - Music, Movies, Merchandise |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2007-03-05 |accessdate=2015-09-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071208213204/http://www.maxnormal.tv/interview2.php |archivedate=8 December 2007 }}</ref> better known by his stage name '''Ninja''', is a [[South Africa]]n rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer, actor, and director. He is best known for being in the [[rap-rave]] group [[Die Antwoord]]. Jones also has had a number of acting roles, including a self-styled role as Ninja in the 2015 [[Neill Blomkamp]] film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-cast-die-antwoord-in-chappie-what-is-zef-was-all-the-obvious-product-pl|title=Why cast Die Antwoord in \"Chappie\"? What is Zef? Was all the obvious product placement good or bad {{!}} ScreenPrism|last=ScreenPrism|website=screenprism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nJones was born in [[Johannesburg|Johannesburg, South Africa]] in 1974. \n\nAccording to [[Die Antwoord]] bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]], Jones has been on the South African hip hop scene since he was 13. He frequented nightclubs where he would develop his skills as a rapper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/23706/1/yo-landi-visser-dark-star|title=Yo-landi Visser\u2019s rise from hood rat to heroine|last=Dazed|date=2015-02-26|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1995\u20131996: The Original Evergreen ===\nJones was part of the South African rap band The Original Evergreen, which were signed to [[Sony Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/FeaturesInterviews/24-Facts-Die-Antwoord-20100204|title=24 Facts: Die Antwoord|last=Barker|first=Jean|date=2010-02-04|website=Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> He released one single with the group, 'Puff the Magik', which was banned from radio for its controversial lyrics about [[marajuana]] usage. He left in 1996 to release a solo album under Chameleon Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1147517-The-Original-Evergreen|title=The Original Evergreen|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2001\u20132002: ''Memoirs Of A Clone'' and Max Normal ===\nIn 2001, Jones released his debut solo album ''Memoirs Of A Clone.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Watkin-Tudor-Jones-Jnr-Memoirs-Of-A-Clone/release/1174704|title=Watkin Tudor Jones Jnr.* \u2013 Memoirs Of A Clone|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, he was the lead vocalist of Max Normal, a hip hop act, which released their debut album entitled ''Songs From The Mall'' in 2001, which he disbanded in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/620890-Max-Normal|title=Max Normal|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> Their last gig was played with [[Faithless]] on the group's 2002 South Africa tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/FeaturesInterviews/24-Facts-Die-Antwoord-20100204|title=24 Facts: Die Antwoord|last=Barker|first=Jean|date=2010-02-04|website=Channel|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n=== 2002\u20132003: ''The Constructus Corporation''===\n{{main|The Constructus Corporation}}\nWhen Jones disbanded Max Normal in early 2002, he and musician Sibot invited [[Markus Wormstorm]] and [[Felix Laband]] to collaborate on The Constructus Corporation project, which resulted in the concept album and graphic novel ''[[The Ziggurat (Constructus Corporation album)|The Ziggurat]],'' released on 3 June 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africandope.co.za/albums/ziggurat.htm |title=Ziggurat \u2013 African Dope Records |publisher=Africandope.co.za |date= |accessdate=2015-09-06}}</ref> \n\nJones asked Anri du Toit, better known as his Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]] to lend vocals for the project. She was credited as Anica the Snuffling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.netzpiloten.de/high-energy-shit-%e2%80%93-%c2%b4die-antwoord%c2%b4-klettern-aus-dem-netz/|title=High Energy Shit \u2013 Die Antwoord klettern aus dem Netz \u2013 Netzpiloten.de|date=2010-08-27|website=Netzpiloten Magazin|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThe Constructus Corporation disbanded in 2003.\n\n=== 2005: ''The Fantastic Kill'' ===\nIn 2005, Jones released his second solo album ''The Fantastic Kill.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Watkin-Tudor-Jones-The-Fantastic-Kill/release/1283679|title=Watkin Tudor Jones \u2013 The Fantastic Kill|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> It was released in France in 2007 as ''MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck Are Fucknrad'' under the name Fucknrad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Fucknrad-MC-Totally-Rad-And-DJ-Fuck-Are-Fucknrad/release/1332825|title=Fucknrad \u2013 MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck Are Fucknrad|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007\u20132008: MaxNormal.TV ===\n{{main|MaxNormal.TV}}\nIn 2007, Jones resurrected and revamped Max Normal as the 'corporate' hip-hop group \"MaxNormal.TV.\" \n\nThe new lineup consisted of Watkin Tudor Jones revising as Max Normal, and Anri du Toit as [[Yolandi Visser]]. The band also featured Neon Don playing various recurring characters and [[Justin De Nobrega]] making instrumentals.\n\nThe group released their debut and only album ''Good Morning South Africa'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/MaxNormalTV-Good-Morning-South-Africa/release/1636872|title=MaxNormal.TV \u2013 Good Morning South Africa|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> A DVD featuring 13 skits, music videos and short films was released in the same year, titled ''Goeie More Zuid Afrika.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/MaxNormalTV-Goeie-More-Zuid-Africa/release/7143103|title=MaxNormal.TV \u2013 Goeie More Zuid Africa|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008\u2013present: Die Antwoord ===\n{{main|Die Antwoord}}\nJones is currently a member of the South African rap-rave group [[Die Antwoord]]. The group was formed by Jones as Ninja, Anri du Toit as [[Yolandi Visser|\u00a5o-Landi Vi$$er]] and producer [[Die Antwoord|Justin De Nobrega]] as HITEK5000 (formerly referred to as DJ Hi-Tek and God). They have since added a second producer Lil2Hood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dieantwoord.com/about/|title=About|website=Die Antwoord|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Die Antwoord is part of the South African counterculture movement known as [[Zef]]. \n\nThe band released their debut album ''[[$O$]]'' in 2009. It was made freely available online and attracted international attention for their music video \"Enter the Ninja\". They briefly signed with [[Interscope Records]], and left after pressure from the label to be more generic. du Toit explained that Interscope \"kept pushing us to be more generic\" in order to make more money: \"If you try to make songs that other people like, your band will always be shit. You always gotta do what you like. If it connects, it's a miracle, but it happened with Die Antwoord.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2012/02/die-antwoords-totally-insane-words-wisdom/|title=Die Antwoord\u2019s Totally Insane Words of Wisdom|date=2012-02-07|website=Spin|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>. They formed their own [[Independent record label|independent label]], Zef Recordz and released their second album [[Tension (Die Antwoord album)|''Tension'']] through it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2011/11/07/dieantwoordleave.html|title=Die Antwoord leave Interscope, will release \"TEN$ION\" on their own new indie label|date=2011-11-07|website=Boing Boing|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nThey have since released 2 other albums; [[Donker Mag|''Donker Mag'']] in 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/die_antwoord_return_with_donker_mag_album_share_new_video|title=Die Antwoord Reveal 'Donker Mag' LP, Share New Video|website=exclaim.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>, and [[Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid|''Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid'']] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19617/reviews/4150414|title=Album Review: Die Antwoord \u2013 Mount Ninji and da Nice Time Kid|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> As well as this, Jones played a self-styled role as Ninja in the 2015 [[Neill Blomkamp]] film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://screenprism.com/insights/article/why-cast-die-antwoord-in-chappie-what-is-zef-was-all-the-obvious-product-pl|title=Why cast Die Antwoord in \"Chappie\"? What is Zef? Was all the obvious product placement good or bad {{!}} ScreenPrism|last=ScreenPrism|website=screenprism.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n=== Zheani Sparkes and sexual assault allegations ===\nIn March 2019, [[Australian]] musician Zheani Sparkes released a [[Diss Track|diss track]] titled \"The Question\" detailing an alleged sexual assault on her by Jones in South Africa in 2013. Sparkes claimed that Jones drugged her, as well as human traffick[ed] her to Africa, and sent sexually explicit photos of her to cast members of [[Chappie (film)|''Chappie'']]. He also expressed having an active interest in her because of her resemblance to his now teenage daughter, Sixteen Jones, who in 2013, was only 8 years old.<ref>{{Citation|title=ZHEANI - THE QUESTION|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY6hCE2D-cc|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allmetaleverything.com/what-happened-with-zheani-and-die-antwoord/|title=What Happened with Zheani and Die Antwoord?!|date=2019-03-11|website=All Metal Everything|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/aussie-rapper-accuses-die-antwoords-ninja-of-trafficking-child-grooming-sexual-abuse-more-in-explosive-new-diss-track/|title=Aussie Rapper Accuses Die Antwoord Of \"Trafficking\", Sexual Abuse & More In Explosive New Diss Track|date=2019-03-21|website=Music Feeds|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nA conflict between Die Antwoord and Sparkes ensued on social media afterwards, where Jones accused Sparkes of catfishing him.<ref>{{Citation|title=DIE ANTWOORD - CATFISH #\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddfa\ud83d\udc31\ud83d\udc1f|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xW_JiG-3DNk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> In September 2019, Sparkes filed a police report in [[Queensland|Queensland, Australia]] formalizing her accusations of sexual assault and [[revenge porn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/zheani-die-antwoord-ninja/|title=Zheani pressing sexual assault charges against Die Antwoord\u2019s Ninja|date=2019-09-16|website=Tone Deaf|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nItalian-American singer [[Dionna Dal Monte]] also accused Jones of sexual assault, which she claimed occurred at a Die Antwoord show in 2014. Jones has vehemently denied all these allegations.<ref name=\"SMH2\">{{Cite news|last=Bossi|first=Dominic|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/australian-woman-accuses-die-antwoord-singer-ninja-of-sexual-assault-20190904-p52nv7.html|title=Australian woman accuses Die Antwoord singer Ninja of sexual assault|date=15 September 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Fight against Andy Butler ===\nIn 2019, a video from 2012 surfaced, showing Jones and Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]] fighting [[Hercules and Love Affair]] founder Andy Butler while calling him insults that could be seen as [[Homophobia|homophobic]], such as \"[[Faggot (slang)|faggot]]\". Butler openly identifies as gay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefullest.com/2017/08/29/hercules-love-affairs-andy-butler-business-gay/|title=Hercules and Love Affair\u2019s Andy Butler on the Business of Being Gay|last=says|first=Karrie|date=2017-08-29|website=The Fullest|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> After fighting him, Visser and Jones alert security staff, and, while crying, Visser claims she was [[Sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] in a bathroom by Butler. Later on in the video, Jones tells her that her performance was \"[[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/die-antwoord-removed-festivals-homophobic-attack-hercules-love-affair-andy-butler-2539949|title=Die Antwoord axed from festivals for 'homophobic attack' on Andy Butler|date=2019-08-20|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Yolandi makes fake sexual assault allegations. One night in Adelaide.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rL1lqrRj9C0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nJones responded on [[Facebook]], claiming that the person who filmed the video edited it to make it seem like he and Visser were in the wrong. He claims that Butler harassed them in the days leading up to the fight, and that it had nothing to do with him being gay. Jones also claimed that he told Visser to act as \"dramatic as possible\" about what Butler did to avoid getting detained by security after the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DieAntwoord/posts/10157192229201971|title=DIE ANTWOORD|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nDie Antwoord was subsequently dropped from the lineup of several upcoming festivals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Norris|first=Chelsey|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/can-die-antwoord-survive-their-latest-in-string-of-scandals-11764757|title=Die Antwoord Reschedules Dallas Show Amid Controversy. We're Not Surprised.|date=26 September 2019|work=Dallas Observer|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones has a daughter, Sixteen Jones, born in 2005 from a previous relationship with Die Antwoord bandmate [[Yolandi Visser]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2oceansvibe.com/2012/02/02/meet-sixteen-the-daugther-of-ninja-and-yolani-vier/|title=Meet Sixteen, The Daugther [sic] Of Ninja And Yolani Vi$$er \u2013 2oceansvibe.com|website=www.2oceansvibe.com|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> He also has 3 adopted children. Tokkie and his sister Meisie were adopted in 2010, and Jemile was adopted in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dieantwoord.com/yoho-magazine/|title=YOHO! MAGAZINE|date=2019-12-03|website=Die Antwoord|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== The Original Evergreen ===\n\n* ''Puff The Magik'' (1995)\n\n=== Max Normal ===\n\n* ''Songs From the Mall'' (2001)\n\n=== The Constructus Corporation ===\n\n* ''[[The Ziggurat (Constructus Corporation album)|The Ziggurat]]'' (2003)\n\n=== MaxNormal.TV ===\n\n* ''Rap Made Easy'' (2007)\n* ''Good Morning South Africa'' (2008)\n\n=== Die Antwoord ===\n\n* ''[[$O$]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Ten$Ion|TEN$ION]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Donker Mag]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Mount Ninji and Da Nice Time Kid]]'' (2016)\n* ''The House of Zef'' (TBA 2020)\n\n=== Solo ===\n\n* ''Memoirs Of A Clone'' (2001)\n* ''The Fantastic Kill'' (2005) (released in 2007 in France as ''MC Totally Rad And DJ Fuck are Fucknrad'')\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''Goeie More Zuid Africa DVD'' (2008)\n* ''Tokoloshe'' (2011)\n* ''Umshimi Wam'' (2011)\n* ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]'' (2015) \u2013 features \"Baby's On Fire\", \"Ugly Boy\", \"Cookie Thumper\" and \"Enter the Ninja\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3333301/die-antwoord-featured-latest-chappie-featurette/|title=Die Antwoord Featured In Latest \u2018Chappie\u2019 Featurette|last=JonathanBarkan|date=2015-02-20|website=Bloody Disgusting!|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{IMDb name|4375135}}\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Watkin+Tudor+Jones Watkin Tudor Jones Discography at discogs.com]\n\n{{Die Antwoord}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Watkin Tudor}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Afrikaans-language singers]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Cape Town culture]]\n[[Category:South African dance musicians]]\n[[Category:South African hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:South African rappers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Die Antwoord members]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Parktown Boys' High School]]\n", "name_user": "2804:431:c7c2:c30f:91bc:245e:d65f:4264", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watkin_Tudor_Jones"}
